  "prompt": "Where does most of the waste come from?",
  "response": "Most of the waste generated globally comes from a variety of sources, including:\n\n1. **Household Waste:** This includes food scraps, packaging materials, paper products, and other everyday items discarded by individuals and families.\n\n2. **Industrial Waste:** Factories and manufacturing plants produce significant amounts of waste, including scraps, chemical byproducts, and packaging materials associated with production processes.\n\n3. **Construction and Demolition Waste:** This type of waste includes materials such as concrete, wood, metals, and plastics generated from construction, renovation, and demolition activities.\n\n4. **Commercial Waste:** Businesses, such as retail stores, restaurants, and offices, generate waste, which can include packaging, food waste, and office supplies.\n\n5. **Agricultural Waste:** Agricultural activities produce waste like crop residues, livestock manure, and unharvested produce.\n\n6. **E-waste:** Discarded electronic devices, such as computers, smartphones, and televisions, contribute to the growing problem of electronic waste.\n\n7. **Medical Waste:** Healthcare facilities generate waste from medical procedures, including sharps, used pharmaceuticals, and contaminated materials.\n\n8. **Municipal Solid Waste (MSW):** This encompasses waste collected by local authorities, including residential, commercial, and institutional waste, excluding industrial and construction waste.\n\nThe composition and amount of waste can vary significantly by region based on factors like culture, economic development, and waste management practices.",
